%I A396593 #18 Jun 07 2026 08:28:07
%S A396593 1,1,6,6,2,1,2,2,3,3,2,1,1,3,2,6,2,1,2,1,1,2,1,1,4,6,1,2,2,2,2,1,1,5,
%T A396593 1,1,5,2,2,2,2,4,4,3,3,1,3,1,2,3,2,1,4,1,2,1,1,1,1,6,4,3,1,2,1,3,4,1,
%U A396593 2,6,3,1,1,1,1,3,5,1,1,2,2,1,3,1,1,1,3,3
%N A396593 Run length transform of A089582.
%C A396593 Define d_0(n) as the n-th prime number. For k >= 0, define the absolute difference sequence d_{k+1}(n) = |d_k(n)-d_k(n+1)|. These are the lengths of consecutive identical runs in d_k(2) for k >= 1.
%C A396593 If Gilbreath's conjecture holds, then d_k(2) consists entirely of 0s and 2s. For n > 2, certain values of d_k(n) can be determined using d_k(2) through an XOR process related to a cellular automaton. Specifically, for a uniformly 0-and-2 sequence in d_k, Rule 90 expands to the analogous sequence in d_{k+1}.
%H A396593 J. C. P. Miller, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1098/rsta.1970.0003">Periodic Forests of Stunted Trees</a>, Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society of London, A. 266 (1970), 63-111.
%H A396593 A. M. Odlyzko, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1090/S0025-5718-1993-1182247-7">Iterated Absolute Values of Differences of Consecutive Primes</a>, Math. Comp. 61 (1993), 373-380.
%H A396593 Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, <a href="https://mathworld.wolfram.com/GilbreathsConjecture.html">Gilbreath's Conjecture</a>.
%t A396593 mx = 200; lst = {}; t = Array[Prime, mx + 2]; Do[t = Abs@ Differences@ t; AppendTo[lst, t[[2]]],{n, mx}]; Most[Length /@ Split[lst]]
%Y A396593 Cf. A089582, A036262.
%K A396593 easy,nonn,new
%O A396593 1,3
%A A396593 _C. Owen Prestwood_, May 29 2026
